sketch:
A proposed route to prove the main theorem is a “naive proof by induction” on the generation of $\Rb\wspc{T}$ from $T$: verify the conclusion in base cases ($f=T$, $f=\log(T)$, $\ldots$); then for a general series $f=\sum_{i<\alpha} r_i e^{\gamma_i}$, assume the conclusion for each map $x\mapsto \gamma_i\circ x$ and try to deduce monotonicity of $x\mapsto f\circ x$. This induction “works very well for $f\in\Jb_\mathfrak{O}^{>0}$”; more precisely:
\begin{prop}\label{monotonicity-J}
  For all $\gamma \in \Jb^{>0}$, the map $x \mapsto \gamma \circ x$ is strictly increasing.
\end{prop}
but “falls short for the general case,” so one additionally uses a “very weak form of mean value property”: for $\gamma\in\Jb_\mathfrak{O}^{>0}$ and $x>y>\mathbb R$,
\[
\frac{\gamma\circ x-\gamma\circ y}{x-y}\preceq \gamma'\circ y\quad \text{at least when}\quad \gamma\circ x-\gamma\circ y\preceq 1\ \text{or}\ (\gamma'\circ y)(x-y)\prec 1.
\]
This condition is “almost trivial” in the base cases $T,\log(T),\ldots$ because the corresponding functions $x\mapsto \log^{\circ n}(x)$ are “strictly increasing and \emph{concave}.” With this weak mean value property in hand, the rest of the induction is then relatively straightforward; in particular, one uses the following lemma:
\begin{lem}\label{weak-mvp}
  For all $\gamma \in \Jb^{>0}$ and all $x, y \in \Ub$ with $x > y > \Rb$, we have:
  \begin{enumerate}
      \item\label{weak-mvp-small} if $\gamma \circ x - \gamma \circ y \preceq 1$, then $\frac{\gamma \circ x - \gamma \circ y}{x - y} \preceq \gamma' \circ y$,
      \item\label{weak-mvp-large} if $\gamma \circ x - \gamma \circ y \succeq 1$, then $(\gamma' \circ y)(x - y) \succeq 1$.
  \end{enumerate}
\end{lem}
yielding “a fairly short proof of the main theorem.”

In the remaining of the introduction, we outline the proof of the main theorem. The groups $\{G_x\}_{x\in\{0,1\}^{\mathbb N}}$ are constructed as wreath-like products (in the sense of \cite{CIOS23a,CIOS23b}) and the construction relies on four ingredients:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \begin{proposition}\label{torsion-free-family}
There exists a countably infinite family $\{B_d\}_{d\geq 1}$  of torsion-free, $4$-generated ICC groups in the class $\mathcal{C}$ which are pairwise not measure equivalent. 
\end{proposition}

\item \begin{proposition}\label{WR}
For every $n\in\mathbb N$,  there exists a property (T) group $V\in\mathcal W\mathcal R(\mathbb F_n^{(\mathbb N)},B)$, where $B$ is a torsion-free (hence, ICC) hyperbolic group.

Moreover, if $\{A_k\}_{k=1}^\infty$ is a sequence of $n$-generated groups, then there exists a property (T) group belonging to $\mathcal W\mathcal R(\bigoplus_{k=1}^\infty A_k,B)$.
\end{proposition}

\item We first use the following theorem.

\begin{theorem}\label{descend}
Let $A$ and $C$ be any countable groups,  and $B$ and $D$ be ICC hyperbolic groups. Assume that $G\in\mathcal W\mathcal R(A,B)$ and $H\in \mathcal{W}\mathcal{R}(C,D)$ are measure equivalent groups. Then the groups $A^{(B)}$ and $C^{(D)}$ are measure equivalent.
\end{theorem}

\item We first use the following theorem.

\begin{theorem}\label{thm:MSinfiniteICCsum}
Suppose $G _i$, $i\in I$, and $H _j$, $j\in J$, are ICC groups in the class $\mathcal{C}$, where $I,J$ are countable. If $G \coloneqq \bigoplus _{i\in I}G _i$ and $H \coloneqq \bigoplus _{j\in J} H _j$ are measure equivalent then $|I|=|J|$ and there exists a bijection $t:I\rightarrow J$ such that $G _i$ is measure equivalent with $H_{t(i)}$ for all $i\in I$.
\end{theorem}
\end{enumerate}
Then the ingredients are combined as follows. Let $\{A_k\}_{k\geq 1}$ be as in (1). For $x\in\{0,1\}^{\mathbb N}$ (viewed as a subset of $\mathbb N$), set $D_x=\bigoplus_{k\in x}A_k$. By (2) there exists a property (T) group $G_x\in\mathcal W\mathcal R(D_x,B)$, and it is torsion-free since it is built from the torsion-free groups $\{A_k\}$ and $B$. If $G_x$ and $G_y$ are measure equivalent, then by the theorem above one gets that $D_x^{(\mathbb N)}\cong\oplus_{k\in x}A_k^{(\mathbb N)}$ and $D_y^{(\mathbb N)}\cong\oplus_{k\in y}A_k^{(\mathbb N)}$ are measure equivalent. Using the defining properties of the sequence $\{A_k\}$ from (1), the theorem above forces $x=y$, yielding a continuum family of pairwise non-measure equivalent groups $\{G_x\}$ as in the main theorem.

The post-theorem introduction does not give a proof sketch for the stated implications in the theorem. It only notes that the remaining implication $(a)\Rightarrow(b)$ is open, and then describes the authors' overall construction/organization: they ``first pinch the Seifert surface to obtain a simpler branched surface, and then perform splittings,'' use a ``greedy splitting algorithm of linear complexity'' given by

